WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:11.720
The Call of the Wild by Jack London Retold by Gina D.B. Clement Copyright, Black

00:11.720 --> 00:19.560
Cat Publishing, 2002

00:19.560 --> 00:24.840
Chapter 1 The Southland Buck did not read the newspapers.

00:24.840 --> 00:30.440
He did not know that there was trouble for every big strong dog in California.

00:30.440 --> 00:34.760
Men found a yellow metal called gold in the Klondike.

00:34.760 --> 00:39.600
They needed big strong dogs with furry coats to work in the north.

00:39.600 --> 00:42.800
Buck lived in a big house in the sunny Santa Clara Valley.

00:42.800 --> 00:46.240
The house was called Judge Miller's Place.

00:46.240 --> 00:50.800
Around the house, there were big gardens, fruit trees and horses.

00:50.800 --> 00:54.800
Buck was born here, and now he was four years old.

00:54.800 --> 00:58.520
There were other dogs, too, but they were not important.

00:58.520 --> 01:00.440
Buck was the king.

01:00.440 --> 01:02.160
Judge Miller's Place was his.

01:02.160 --> 01:04.920
He swam and hunted with the judge's sons.

01:04.920 --> 01:07.360
He walked with the judge's daughters.

01:07.360 --> 01:11.560
He carried the judge's grandsons on his back and played with them.

01:11.560 --> 01:16.200
In the winter, Buck sat at the judge's feet in front of the fire.

01:16.200 --> 01:21.760
Buck's father was a big Saint Bernard, and his mother was a Scottish sheepdog.

01:21.760 --> 01:27.520
Buck weighed 140 pounds, and he was a happy and handsome dog.

01:27.520 --> 01:33.640
In the fall of 1897, men from all over the world went to the Klondike.

01:33.640 --> 01:39.200
They wanted to find gold, but Buck did not read the newspapers.

01:39.200 --> 01:43.640
Manuel was the gardener's helper, and he needed money for his big family.

01:43.640 --> 01:48.360
One evening the judge was out of the house, and Manuel and Buck went for a walk.

01:48.360 --> 01:53.320
No one saw them leave, and only one man saw them at the railway station.

01:53.320 --> 01:57.400
The man talked to Manuel and gave him some money.

01:57.400 --> 02:00.320
Then Manuel tied a rope around Buck's neck.

02:00.320 --> 02:04.520
Buck let Manuel put the rope around his neck because he was his friend.

02:04.520 --> 02:08.360
But when the other man pulled the rope, Buck could not breathe.

02:08.360 --> 02:12.360
He was angry, and he jumped at the man.

02:12.360 --> 02:15.000
The man caught him, and suddenly Buck was on his back.

02:15.000 --> 02:18.600
His tongue was out of his mouth, and he was unable to move.

02:18.600 --> 02:22.720
In the past, no one ever did this to him.

02:22.720 --> 02:26.600
The two men put him on the train in the baggage car.

02:26.600 --> 02:29.880
When Buck woke up, the train was moving.

02:29.880 --> 02:31.800
He was angry.

02:31.800 --> 02:34.880
The man watched him, but Buck was too quick.

02:34.880 --> 02:38.440
He bit the man's hand.

02:38.440 --> 02:44.600
That evening, the man took Buck to the back room of a saloon in San Francisco.

02:44.600 --> 02:46.480
The saloon keeper looked at his hand.

02:46.480 --> 02:48.920
I only got $50 for it.

02:48.920 --> 02:50.480
The man said.

02:50.480 --> 02:52.000
How much did the other man get?

02:52.000 --> 02:55.480
The saloon keeper asked, $100.

02:55.480 --> 02:56.480
That makes $150.

02:56.480 --> 02:59.160
That's a good price for a dog like him.

02:59.160 --> 03:02.880
Come on, help me put him into the crate.

03:02.880 --> 03:08.480
Buck tried to attack the two men, but they pulled the rope again and again.

03:08.480 --> 03:10.560
Buck suffered terribly.

03:10.560 --> 03:14.080
His neck, throat, and tongue hurt a lot.

03:14.080 --> 03:18.480
The men took off the rope and threw him into a crate.

03:18.480 --> 03:21.700
Buck spent the night in the back room of the saloon.

03:21.700 --> 03:23.720
He was very angry.

03:23.720 --> 03:26.560
He could not understand why he was there.

03:26.560 --> 03:28.840
What did these strange men want?

03:28.840 --> 03:31.400
Why was he a prisoner in a crate?

03:31.400 --> 03:33.560
Where was the judge?

03:33.560 --> 03:38.040
The next morning, four men took the crate to the railway station.

03:38.040 --> 03:43.240
They put it on a train that was going to the north.

03:43.240 --> 03:48.720
For two days and two nights, Buck did not eat or drink.

03:48.720 --> 03:51.680
He was confused and angry.

03:51.680 --> 03:53.640
Men on the train laughed at him.

03:53.640 --> 03:55.680
He threw himself against the crate.

03:55.680 --> 04:00.440
He growled and barked at the men.

04:00.440 --> 04:04.440
Buck was very thirsty, but he had no water.

04:04.440 --> 04:07.720
His tongue and throat were very dry.

04:07.720 --> 04:12.040
His eyes were red and his anger grew.

04:12.040 --> 04:14.320
He was glad for one thing.

04:14.320 --> 04:16.680
The rope was off his neck.

04:16.680 --> 04:24.160
He did not want another rope around his neck.

04:24.160 --> 04:26.240
Exercise five.

04:26.240 --> 04:38.640
Did you know one, two, three, two, three, two, three, two, three, two, three, two, three, two,

04:39.040 --> 04:44.760
Four men carried the crate to a garden with a high wall.

04:44.760 --> 04:47.920
A fat man with a red sweater looked at him.

04:47.920 --> 04:50.180
Buck threw himself against the crate.

04:50.180 --> 04:51.700
He growled and barked.

04:51.700 --> 04:54.380
The man brought a hatchet and a clow.

04:54.380 --> 04:58.440
Are you going to take him out now?

04:58.440 --> 05:00.000
Asked one of the men?

05:00.000 --> 05:01.340
Sure, said.

05:01.340 --> 05:04.820
Are you going to take him out now?" asked one of the men.

05:04.820 --> 05:05.820
Sure.

05:05.820 --> 05:07.620
The man said.

05:07.620 --> 05:10.900
He hit the crate with a hatchet to open it.

05:10.900 --> 05:13.340
The four men ran away.

05:13.340 --> 05:16.900
They went to sit on the high wall to watch the show.

05:16.900 --> 05:19.620
Buck threw himself against the wood of the crate.

05:19.620 --> 05:21.980
He bit it and growled.

05:21.980 --> 05:23.980
He wanted to get out.

05:23.980 --> 05:26.780
The man with the hatchet opened the crate.

05:26.780 --> 05:30.500
Then he put down the hatchet and took the club.

05:30.500 --> 05:33.300
Buck was really a red-eyed devil.

05:33.300 --> 05:37.620
His hair stood up and his eyes were red with anger.

05:37.620 --> 05:41.900
He jumped straight at the man and his mouth was ready to bite.

05:41.900 --> 05:46.140
At that moment, the man hit him with the club.

05:46.140 --> 05:49.780
He fell to the ground on his back.

05:49.780 --> 05:53.300
This was the first time he was hit with a club.

05:53.300 --> 05:55.380
He did not understand.

05:55.380 --> 05:58.220
He jumped at the man again.

05:58.220 --> 06:01.700
And again the man hit him with the club.

06:01.700 --> 06:03.940
He fell to the ground again.

06:03.940 --> 06:06.740
This time Buck knew that it was the club.

06:06.740 --> 06:10.340
But his anger was so great that he did not stop.

06:10.340 --> 06:16.140
He jumped at the man a dozen times and a dozen times the club hit him.

06:16.140 --> 06:20.100
There was blood on his nose, mouth and ears.

06:20.100 --> 06:22.900
Then the man hit him very hard on the nose.

06:22.900 --> 06:24.780
The pain was terrible.

06:24.780 --> 06:26.780
It was agony.

06:26.780 --> 06:31.340
Buck jumped at the man again and the man threw him to the ground.

06:31.340 --> 06:34.140
Buck did not move for some time.

06:34.140 --> 06:37.060
He knows how to teach a dog a lesson.

06:37.060 --> 06:39.460
Said one of the four men.

06:39.460 --> 06:42.380
Then they returned to the train station.

06:42.380 --> 06:45.580
Buck slowly opened his eyes.

06:45.580 --> 06:47.700
He could not move.

06:47.700 --> 06:50.940
He watched the man in the red sweater.

06:50.940 --> 06:54.300
The fat man was reading the saloonkeeper's letter and said,

06:54.460 --> 06:56.380
Your name is Buck.

06:56.380 --> 06:57.380
Well Buck.

06:57.380 --> 06:59.260
He said in a friendly voice,

06:59.260 --> 07:01.540
Now you know your place.

07:01.540 --> 07:04.220
Be a good dog and we'll be friends.

07:04.220 --> 07:07.860
Be a bad dog and I must use my club again.

07:07.860 --> 07:09.660
Understand?

07:09.660 --> 07:12.900
As he spoke, he touched Buck's head.

07:12.900 --> 07:15.740
Buck was angry inside.

07:15.740 --> 07:18.100
But he did not move.

07:18.100 --> 07:23.460
When the man brought him water and meat, Buck drank and ate.

07:23.460 --> 07:27.300
He learned that a man with a club was stronger than him.

07:27.300 --> 07:29.220
He never forgot it.

07:29.220 --> 07:32.420
Life was now fiercer.

07:32.420 --> 07:35.540
Each day other dogs came.

07:35.540 --> 07:38.780
The man in the red sweater hit many dogs.

07:38.780 --> 07:43.140
Buck understood that a dog must obey a man with a club.

07:43.140 --> 07:45.180
He was a master.

07:45.180 --> 07:50.420
One dog did not obey and he was killed.

07:50.420 --> 07:54.500
Men often came to talk to the man in the red sweater.

07:54.500 --> 07:58.980
When they paid money, the men took one or more of the dogs.

07:58.980 --> 08:02.020
Those dogs never came back.

08:02.020 --> 08:03.380
Where did they go?

08:03.380 --> 08:04.820
Buck thought.

08:04.820 --> 08:07.940
He was afraid of the future.

08:07.940 --> 08:11.780
One day, a short man came to look at Buck.

08:11.780 --> 08:14.020
The man spoke bad English.

08:14.020 --> 08:15.420
That's a strong dog.

08:15.420 --> 08:16.500
How much?

08:16.500 --> 08:17.700
$300.

08:17.700 --> 08:19.580
Said the man in the red sweater.

08:19.660 --> 08:21.620
And it's a gift at that price.

08:21.620 --> 08:23.540
Perot smiled.

08:23.540 --> 08:26.500
The price of dogs was high at that time.

08:26.500 --> 08:31.820
Perot knew dogs and he knew Buck was an excellent dog.

08:31.820 --> 08:34.820
Buck saw money passed between the two men.

08:34.820 --> 08:39.380
He was not surprised when he and a Newfoundland dog called Curly

08:39.380 --> 08:42.340
were taken away by the small man.

08:42.340 --> 08:46.420
He took them to a ship called the Norwall.

08:46.420 --> 08:50.860
From the ship, he and Curly looked back at Seattle.

08:50.860 --> 08:55.420
It was the last time they saw the warm Southland.

08:55.420 --> 08:58.900
Perot took Buck and Curly to Francois.

08:58.900 --> 09:03.700
Perot was a French Canadian, but Francois was half Indian

09:03.700 --> 09:06.180
and had very dark skin.

09:06.180 --> 09:10.180
Buck did not like these men, but he respected them.

09:10.180 --> 09:14.220
He learned that Perot and Francois were calm and fair.

09:14.220 --> 09:17.380
They knew everything about dogs.

09:17.380 --> 09:19.780
There were two other dogs on the ship.

09:19.780 --> 09:23.660
One was a big white dog called Spitz.

09:23.660 --> 09:27.900
He seemed friendly, but he was not honest.

09:27.900 --> 09:30.980
He smiled when he tried to take Buck's food.

09:30.980 --> 09:33.980
Francois was fast and hit Spitz.

09:33.980 --> 09:38.820
From this moment, Buck began to like him.

09:38.820 --> 09:41.620
The other dog was called Dave.

09:41.620 --> 09:45.180
He was unfriendly and always wanted to be alone.

09:45.180 --> 09:50.380
Dave ate and slept and was interested in nothing.

09:50.380 --> 09:53.340
Day and night the ship sailed.

09:53.340 --> 09:57.100
Every day was the same, but Buck noticed

09:57.100 --> 10:00.300
that the weather was colder.

10:00.300 --> 10:05.380
Finally, one morning the Norwall's engine stopped.

10:05.380 --> 10:08.180
Buck and the other dogs were excited.

10:08.180 --> 10:10.300
Something was happening.

10:10.300 --> 10:14.660
Francois leashed the dogs and took them outside.

10:14.660 --> 10:17.060
At the first step, Buck's feet went down

10:17.060 --> 10:19.660
into something white and soft.

10:19.660 --> 10:21.380
He jumped back.

10:21.380 --> 10:24.420
More of this white stuff was falling from the sky

10:24.420 --> 10:26.420
and fell on Buck.

10:26.420 --> 10:30.980
He shook himself, but more fell on him.

10:30.980 --> 10:36.260
He smelled it curiously, then tasted some on his tongue.

10:36.260 --> 10:41.180
It was like fire, and the next moment, it disappeared.

10:41.180 --> 10:43.180
This confused him.

10:43.180 --> 10:46.780
He tried it again with the same result.

10:46.780 --> 10:49.460
People looked at him and laughed.

10:49.460 --> 10:51.420
It was his first snow.

10:55.060 --> 11:00.380
Chapter 3, The Law of Club and Fang.

11:00.380 --> 11:03.860
Buck's first day at Daihee Beach was terrible.

11:03.860 --> 11:06.140
What a change from his comfortable, happy life

11:06.140 --> 11:09.620
with the judge in the sunny Southland.

11:09.620 --> 11:12.500
Here, there was no peace or rest.

11:12.500 --> 11:15.580
There was only confusion and noise.

11:15.580 --> 11:19.220
There was danger everywhere, because these dogs and men

11:19.220 --> 11:21.180
were not city dogs and men.

11:21.180 --> 11:25.780
They only knew the law of club and fang.

11:25.780 --> 11:28.420
Buck never saw dogs like these.

11:28.420 --> 11:30.700
They fought like wolves.

11:30.700 --> 11:33.340
He learned this by watching Curly.

11:33.340 --> 11:35.860
She wanted to make friends with a husky.

11:35.860 --> 11:39.460
The husky jumped on Curly, and he tore her face from eye

11:39.460 --> 11:41.460
to mouth.

11:41.460 --> 11:44.140
Wolves and huskies fight like this.

11:44.140 --> 11:47.260
They attack and then jump away.

11:47.260 --> 11:49.500
But this fight was not finished.

11:49.500 --> 11:53.260
30 or 40 huskies came and made a circle around the fight.

11:53.260 --> 11:57.620
Curly attacked her enemy, but the husky bit her again.

11:57.620 --> 12:02.300
She fell to the ground and never stood up again.

12:02.300 --> 12:05.180
The other huskies moved in, and suddenly,

12:05.180 --> 12:07.220
she was under them.

12:07.220 --> 12:11.420
Buck saw Spitz run away with his red tongue out of his mouth.

12:11.420 --> 12:13.180
He was laughing.

12:13.180 --> 12:16.300
Curly was dead in the snow.

12:16.300 --> 12:19.580
Her body was almost in pieces.

12:19.580 --> 12:23.020
Buck often saw this scene in his dreams.

12:23.020 --> 12:27.940
He understood that when a dog was injured, that was the end.

12:27.940 --> 12:33.780
Spitz laughed again, and from that moment, Buck hated him.

12:33.780 --> 12:36.260
Soon Buck had another surprise.

12:36.260 --> 12:38.700
Francois put a harness on him.

12:38.700 --> 12:42.580
Buck remembered the harnesses on horses at home.

12:42.580 --> 12:45.540
So now he must work like a horse.

12:45.540 --> 12:50.740
He must pull the sled to the forest to get firewood.

12:50.740 --> 12:55.980
He was offended, but he decided to work and do his best.

12:55.980 --> 13:00.500
He worked with Spitz and Dave and learned a lot from them.

13:00.500 --> 13:06.900
He learned to stop when Francois said, and to go when he said,

13:06.900 --> 13:08.460
Marsh!

13:08.460 --> 13:10.340
Those three are very good dogs.

13:10.340 --> 13:12.180
Francois told Perot.

13:12.180 --> 13:15.940
Buck pulls well and learns quickly.

13:15.940 --> 13:22.020
That afternoon, Perot bought two huskies called Billy and Joe.

13:22.020 --> 13:23.700
They were brothers.

13:23.700 --> 13:28.060
Billy was very friendly, but Joe was the opposite.

13:28.140 --> 13:33.020
In the evening, Perot bought another dog called Solax.

13:33.020 --> 13:36.540
He was an old husky with only one eye.

13:36.540 --> 13:40.780
He made no friends and wanted to be alone.

13:40.780 --> 13:45.060
That night, Buck had another problem.

13:45.060 --> 13:46.980
Where could he sleep?

13:46.980 --> 13:49.900
Francois and Perot were in their tent.

13:49.900 --> 13:53.380
When Buck tried to enter, they shouted angrily at him.

13:53.380 --> 13:57.140
It was terribly cold and windy outside.

13:57.140 --> 14:02.020
Buck tried to sleep in the snow, but it was too cold.

14:02.020 --> 14:04.580
Buck walked sadly around the tent.

14:04.580 --> 14:08.700
He looked for the other dogs, but he could not find them.

14:08.700 --> 14:10.500
Where were they?

14:10.500 --> 14:13.340
Buck was very cold and unhappy.

14:13.340 --> 14:16.140
He did not know what to do.

14:16.140 --> 14:18.940
Suddenly, he fell into a hole.

14:18.940 --> 14:24.420
He felt something move and then heard a friendly bark.

14:24.420 --> 14:29.060
With the snow, in the warm hole, he saw Billy.

14:29.060 --> 14:34.500
Billy licked Buck's face with his warm, wet tongue.

14:34.500 --> 14:36.500
Another lesson.

14:36.500 --> 14:39.780
So that was how the dog slept.

14:39.780 --> 14:42.420
Buck chose a place and made a hole.

14:42.420 --> 14:45.780
In a minute, he was warm and asleep.

14:45.780 --> 14:49.780
He slept well, but had bad dreams.

14:49.780 --> 14:52.940
The noises of the camp woke him up the next morning.

14:53.300 --> 14:54.580
What did I say?

14:54.580 --> 14:56.740
Francois shouted to Perot.

14:56.740 --> 14:58.900
That Buck learns quickly.

14:58.900 --> 15:00.860
Perot smiled.

15:00.860 --> 15:03.860
He was a courier for the Canadian government.

15:03.860 --> 15:06.300
He transported important documents,

15:06.300 --> 15:08.860
and he needed the best dogs.

15:08.860 --> 15:11.740
He bought three dogs that morning.

15:11.740 --> 15:14.620
Now there were nine dogs in a harness,

15:14.620 --> 15:18.780
and they were going up the Daihi Canyon.

15:18.780 --> 15:22.180
The work was hard, but Buck liked it.

15:22.180 --> 15:26.420
He was surprised that Dave and Solax were not bored now.

15:26.420 --> 15:30.620
Pulling in a harness was their job, and they were happy.

15:30.620 --> 15:33.700
All the dogs were alert and active.

15:33.700 --> 15:35.580
Billy was the sled dog.

15:35.580 --> 15:37.820
He was nearest to the sled.

15:37.820 --> 15:39.820
Dave was in front of him.

15:39.820 --> 15:41.620
Then there was Buck.

15:41.620 --> 15:43.980
In front of them were the other dogs.

15:43.980 --> 15:46.420
Spitz was the leader in front.

15:46.420 --> 15:49.300
Dave and Solax were Buck's teachers.

15:49.300 --> 15:51.140
When Buck pulled the wrong way,

15:51.140 --> 15:54.020
Dave always bit his leg lightly.

15:54.020 --> 15:55.900
Buck learned quickly.

15:56.940 --> 15:59.540
It was a hard journey up the canyon,

15:59.540 --> 16:02.500
through sheep camp and into the mountains.

16:03.740 --> 16:07.140
That night, they camped at Lake Bennett.

16:07.140 --> 16:10.260
Thousands of gold miners were there.

16:10.260 --> 16:14.580
Buck made his hole in the snow and slept well.

16:15.740 --> 16:17.900
Very early the next morning,

16:17.900 --> 16:20.780
Buck and his team started pulling the sled again.

16:22.140 --> 16:27.140
That day, they traveled 40 miles on a good trail.

16:27.220 --> 16:31.020
But the next day, there was no trail.

16:31.020 --> 16:34.900
The dogs worked harder, and they traveled slowly.

16:36.420 --> 16:39.340
Perot usually went in front of the dogs.

16:39.340 --> 16:42.740
With his snow shoes, he made the snow flat.

16:42.740 --> 16:45.780
Francois guided the sled from behind.

16:45.780 --> 16:47.540
Perot was in a hurry.

16:47.620 --> 16:51.900
He knew all about ice, and this was very important.

16:51.900 --> 16:55.300
In the fall, the ice was very thin.

16:56.220 --> 17:00.860
Day after day, Buck worked hard and pulled the sled.

17:00.860 --> 17:03.620
The dog started before it was light,

17:03.620 --> 17:06.660
and stopped in the evening after dark.

17:06.660 --> 17:09.860
They ate a piece of fish and went to sleep.

17:09.860 --> 17:12.420
Buck was always hungry.

17:12.420 --> 17:16.020
Every day he ate a pound and a half of fish,

17:16.100 --> 17:18.580
but it was never enough.

17:18.580 --> 17:22.260
One day, he saw another dog called Pike

17:22.260 --> 17:24.740
steal meat from Perot.

17:24.740 --> 17:29.300
Buck did the same the next day, and no one saw him.

17:29.300 --> 17:32.620
Buck was learning to live in the hostile Northland.

17:32.620 --> 17:37.300
In the Southland, he never stole, but he was never hungry.

17:37.300 --> 17:41.900
In the Southland, there was the law of love and friendship.

17:41.900 --> 17:45.820
The man with the red sweater taught him the law of club

17:45.820 --> 17:47.660
and Fang.

17:47.660 --> 17:50.500
He learned to eat all kinds of food.

17:50.500 --> 17:54.380
He learned to fight and became very clever.

17:54.380 --> 17:57.260
He became stronger and more primitive.

17:57.260 --> 18:01.420
The natural forces inside of him became alive.

18:01.420 --> 18:03.940
It was easy for Buck to fight like a wolf

18:03.940 --> 18:06.300
because it was in his blood.

18:06.300 --> 18:10.020
At night, he looked at a star and howled.

18:10.980 --> 18:14.620
Like his ancestors did long ago.

18:14.620 --> 18:17.140
Buck was following his instinct.

18:19.820 --> 18:22.420
Chapter 4, The Attack.

18:24.020 --> 18:28.340
The primitive spirit of his ancestors was strong in Buck,

18:28.340 --> 18:31.420
and under the harsh conditions of his new life,

18:31.420 --> 18:33.500
this spirit grew.

18:33.500 --> 18:37.100
He hated Spitz more and more,

18:37.100 --> 18:39.260
but he did not want to start a fight.

18:39.260 --> 18:41.460
Buck was careful.

18:41.460 --> 18:44.260
He did nothing without thinking.

18:44.260 --> 18:47.140
Spitz always showed his teeth to Buck.

18:47.140 --> 18:49.060
He wanted to start a fight.

18:49.060 --> 18:53.780
Buck knew that a fight meant the death of one or the other.

18:53.780 --> 18:57.660
One night, the fight almost happened.

18:57.660 --> 19:00.100
They stopped at Lake La Beres.

19:00.100 --> 19:04.340
It was snowing heavily and the wind was strong and cold.

19:04.340 --> 19:07.660
Perot and Francois made a fire on the ice.

19:07.660 --> 19:09.540
Buck made a hole in the snow.

19:09.540 --> 19:11.980
It was warm and comfortable.

19:11.980 --> 19:15.220
He did not want to leave it to get his piece of fish.

19:15.220 --> 19:17.420
When Buck finished eating the fish,

19:17.420 --> 19:20.820
he went back to his hole and found Spitz in it.

19:21.900 --> 19:24.460
Buck did not want to fight with Spitz,

19:24.460 --> 19:27.180
but this was too much.

19:27.180 --> 19:29.500
He jumped on Spitz with great anger.

19:29.500 --> 19:31.820
Spitz was very surprised.

19:31.820 --> 19:34.780
He knew Buck was big, but he did not know.

19:34.780 --> 19:36.540
He was so wild.

19:36.540 --> 19:38.820
Francois was surprised too.

19:38.820 --> 19:40.660
Aha! He cried to Buck.

19:40.660 --> 19:43.300
Give it to him! Give it to him!

19:43.300 --> 19:45.340
Both dogs wanted a fight.

19:45.340 --> 19:48.980
They circled each other and waited for a chance to jump in.

19:50.100 --> 19:51.620
Suddenly, Perot shouted,

19:51.620 --> 19:54.220
Ah! Ah! Ah!

19:54.220 --> 19:57.740
And they saw about a hundred thin, hungry dogs.

19:57.740 --> 19:59.620
They came from an Indian village

19:59.620 --> 20:01.620
and they were looking for food.

20:01.620 --> 20:04.380
Perot and Francois hit them with their clubs,

20:04.380 --> 20:07.460
but the hungry dog showed their teeth and attacked.

20:07.460 --> 20:09.580
One dog found the food box.

20:09.580 --> 20:13.340
And in a moment, 20 dogs ate the bread in the meat.

20:13.340 --> 20:16.900
The smell of food made them crazy.

20:16.900 --> 20:19.100
The dogs looked like skeletons

20:19.100 --> 20:22.500
with wild eyes and sharp fangs.

20:22.500 --> 20:26.460
Three of them attacked Buck and bit his head and shoulders.

20:26.460 --> 20:30.980
Dave and Sallax fought courageously side by side.

20:30.980 --> 20:33.180
Joe attacked the dogs too.

20:33.180 --> 20:36.940
Buck bit a dog in the neck and tasted its blood.

20:36.940 --> 20:39.380
The taste of blood made him fiercer.

20:39.380 --> 20:44.100
He jumped on another dog and then felt teeth in his own neck.

20:44.100 --> 20:47.020
Spitz was attacking him from the side.

20:47.020 --> 20:50.540
Perot and Francois came with clubs to help their dogs.

20:50.540 --> 20:54.620
The hungry dogs ran away, but only for a moment.

20:54.620 --> 20:57.340
When the two men ran back to save their food,

20:57.340 --> 20:59.180
the dogs attacked again.

20:59.180 --> 21:01.180
The terrible fight continued.

21:04.020 --> 21:09.020
Later, the nine team dogs ran away and hid in the forest.

21:09.380 --> 21:11.540
They passed the night there.

21:11.540 --> 21:17.820
Each dog was hurt in four or five places and Joe lost his eye.

21:17.820 --> 21:21.740
Early the next morning, they slowly walked back to camp.

21:21.740 --> 21:24.140
Perot and Francois were angry.

21:24.140 --> 21:28.860
Half their food was gone and one dog ate Perot's shoe.

21:28.860 --> 21:31.820
Francois looked at the poor dogs and said,

21:31.820 --> 21:37.980
Ah, my friends, perhaps those bites will make your crazy dogs.

21:37.980 --> 21:39.660
What do you think, Perot?

21:39.660 --> 21:41.940
Perot said nothing.

21:41.940 --> 21:46.820
There were 400 miles between him and Dawson.

21:46.820 --> 21:49.780
He hoped his dogs were not crazy.

21:49.780 --> 21:53.940
After two hours of hard work, the team started traveling.

21:53.940 --> 21:57.300
The next part of the trail was the most difficult.

21:57.300 --> 22:02.340
The 30-mile river was not frozen because the water moved too quickly.

22:02.340 --> 22:06.580
It took six days to travel those terrible 30 miles.

22:06.580 --> 22:13.700
They were terrible because every step was dangerous for the dogs and the men.

22:13.700 --> 22:20.340
They found 12 ice bridges across the river and Perot fell through all of them.

22:20.340 --> 22:22.980
His long stick saved him.

22:22.980 --> 22:27.420
The temperature was 50 degrees Fahrenheit below zero.

22:27.420 --> 22:34.340
Each time Perot fell into the icy water, he built a fire to dry and warm himself.

22:34.340 --> 22:37.540
Perot was not afraid of anything.

22:37.540 --> 22:40.980
This is why he was a government courier.

22:40.980 --> 22:42.820
He was often in danger.

22:42.820 --> 22:48.660
Once, the sled with Buck and Dave fell through the ice.

22:48.660 --> 22:54.700
When Perot and Francois pulled them out of the river, they were covered with ice.

22:54.700 --> 22:58.500
The men built a fire to save the dogs.

22:58.500 --> 23:03.740
When they arrived in Hootalinkwa, Buck and the other dogs were exhausted.

23:03.740 --> 23:08.020
However, they were late and Perot made them run faster.

23:08.020 --> 23:14.940
In three days, they traveled 110 miles and reached a place called Five Fingers.

23:14.940 --> 23:18.260
Buck's feet were not as hard as the feet of the Huskies.

23:18.260 --> 23:22.700
His feet were still soft because of his comfortable life with the judge.

23:22.700 --> 23:25.820
His feet hurt a lot all day.

23:25.820 --> 23:29.980
That night at the camp, he lay down like a dead dog.

23:29.980 --> 23:33.980
He was hungry, but he could not walk to get his fish.

23:33.980 --> 23:36.500
So Francois brought it to him.

23:36.500 --> 23:41.260
Every evening after dinner, Francois massaged Buck's feet for half an hour.

23:41.260 --> 23:44.140
He made four little shoes for Buck.

23:44.140 --> 23:46.700
Now Buck was more comfortable.

23:46.700 --> 23:51.340
One morning, Francois forgot the shoes and Buck lay on his back with his feet in the

23:51.340 --> 23:52.620
air.

23:52.620 --> 23:55.820
He did not want to move without his shoes.

23:55.820 --> 24:01.900
Where his feet grew hard and the shoes were not necessary.

24:01.900 --> 24:05.540
Chapter 5 The Big Fight

24:05.540 --> 24:09.060
At Pelly River one morning, Dolly suddenly went crazy.

24:09.060 --> 24:13.900
She howled like a wolf and then jumped at Buck.

24:13.900 --> 24:17.500
Buck knew this was something terrible and ran away.

24:17.500 --> 24:19.260
Dolly was behind him.

24:19.260 --> 24:20.820
Buck was afraid.

24:20.820 --> 24:26.700
He ran as fast as he could through the woods, across the ice, and back to the river.

24:26.700 --> 24:29.180
Dolly was one step behind him.

24:29.180 --> 24:31.540
Buck could hear her growling angrily.

24:31.540 --> 24:32.540
Buck!

24:32.540 --> 24:33.540
Buck!

24:33.540 --> 24:35.340
Francois called.

24:35.340 --> 24:39.180
Francois can save me, Buck thought, and ran to him.

24:39.180 --> 24:41.740
Francois had an axe ready in his hand.

24:41.740 --> 24:46.420
As Buck ran past him, the axe fell down on Dolly's head.

24:46.420 --> 24:48.740
Buck lay down near the sled.

24:48.740 --> 24:50.780
He was exhausted.

24:50.780 --> 24:53.140
This was Spitz's opportunity.

24:53.140 --> 24:56.900
He jumped at Buck and bit him very hard.

24:56.900 --> 24:59.420
Francois saw this and hit Spitz.

24:59.420 --> 25:01.420
That Spitz is a devil.

25:01.420 --> 25:02.420
Said Perot.

25:02.420 --> 25:05.660
Someday he will kill Buck.

25:05.660 --> 25:07.300
Buck is like two devils.

25:07.300 --> 25:09.420
I know this for sure.

25:09.420 --> 25:13.020
Someday Buck will get very angry and eat up Spitz.

25:13.020 --> 25:15.060
Francois said.

25:15.060 --> 25:20.140
From then on, it was war between Spitz and Buck.

25:20.140 --> 25:23.780
Spitz was the lead dog and master of the team.

25:23.780 --> 25:26.380
Buck wanted to be the lead dog.

25:26.380 --> 25:28.660
It was part of his nature.

25:28.660 --> 25:31.620
Spitz knew this and hated him.

25:31.620 --> 25:36.100
Buck was dangerous because he was strong, clever, and patient.

25:36.100 --> 25:40.700
When the dogs made mistakes, Buck protected them from Spitz.

25:40.700 --> 25:46.780
One morning, Pike did not want to get up, and Spitz looked for him everywhere.

25:46.780 --> 25:52.060
When he found Pike, he jumped at him, but Buck suddenly attacked Spitz.

25:52.060 --> 25:56.140
Francois whipped Buck with all his strength.

25:56.140 --> 25:58.300
This did not stop Buck.

25:58.300 --> 26:01.820
Francois whipped him again and again.

26:01.820 --> 26:06.860
The other dogs saw this and it became difficult for Spitz to lead them.

26:06.860 --> 26:11.260
Day after day, Buck protected the other dogs from Spitz.

26:11.260 --> 26:14.940
Buck did it secretly when Francois was not looking.

26:15.020 --> 26:18.100
Things began to change on the team.

26:18.100 --> 26:21.340
The dogs did not respect or obey Spitz.

26:21.340 --> 26:23.580
The team became worse.

26:23.580 --> 26:28.780
There was always more trouble, and Buck was responsible for it.

26:28.780 --> 26:31.900
Francois was worried about Buck and Spitz.

26:31.900 --> 26:36.380
Those dogs will have a big fight one day, he thought.

26:36.380 --> 26:39.500
But the days passed without a big fight.

26:39.500 --> 26:44.020
They arrived in Dawson City on a cold, gray afternoon.

26:44.020 --> 26:49.620
For many men and dogs in Dawson, the dogs did all kinds of work.

26:49.620 --> 26:55.220
Buck met some Southland dogs, but most of the dogs were Huskies.

26:55.220 --> 27:01.900
At night, there was the Aurora Borealis and the stars danced in the sky.

27:01.900 --> 27:12.300
Every night at nine o'clock, at twelve, and at three, all the dogs howled together.

27:12.300 --> 27:14.340
Not like to howl with them.

27:14.340 --> 27:19.100
It was a strange song of the night from thousands of years ago.

27:19.100 --> 27:22.340
It was the song of Buck's ancestors.

27:22.340 --> 27:26.340
It was about the difficulties of life.

27:26.340 --> 27:29.260
They left Dawson after seven days.

27:29.260 --> 27:31.220
Pirro had some important letters.

27:31.220 --> 27:35.300
He wanted to return to Dai as fast as possible.

27:35.300 --> 27:38.980
The dogs were rested and in good condition.

27:38.980 --> 27:43.660
On the first day they traveled fifty miles, and on the second day they were on the Yukon

27:43.660 --> 27:46.260
River near Pelly.

27:46.260 --> 27:48.940
Francois had many problems with the team.

27:48.940 --> 27:51.860
The dogs did not work well together.

27:51.860 --> 27:54.100
Buck and Spitz hated each other.

27:54.100 --> 27:56.900
The other dogs did not respect Spitz.

27:56.900 --> 27:59.780
They were not afraid of him anymore.

27:59.780 --> 28:05.060
Francois often stopped the sled because the dogs were fighting.

28:05.060 --> 28:08.620
Francois knew that Buck caused the trouble.

28:08.620 --> 28:13.620
But Buck was very clever, and Francois never saw him.

28:13.620 --> 28:18.100
Buck worked hard, and he loved pulling the sled.

28:18.100 --> 28:22.500
One night after dinner, Dubb found a snow rabbit.

28:22.500 --> 28:25.700
In a moment all the dogs were running after it.

28:25.700 --> 28:30.460
Nearby it was a camp of the Northwest police with fifty dogs.

28:30.460 --> 28:34.100
The fifty dogs started running after the rabbit too.

28:34.100 --> 28:37.220
The rabbit ran quickly on the soft snow.

28:37.220 --> 28:39.820
But it was more difficult for the dogs.

28:39.820 --> 28:43.940
Buck led the pack of sixty dogs, and he was very happy.

28:43.940 --> 28:47.780
He was hunting his food, and he felt alive.

28:47.780 --> 28:52.460
His splendid body moved forward in the white moonlight.

28:52.460 --> 28:55.300
In the end, Spitz caught the rabbit.

28:55.300 --> 28:58.980
He broke its back with his teeth and threw it in the air.

28:58.980 --> 29:00.740
Buck attacked Spitz.

29:00.740 --> 29:02.900
The dogs fell in the snow.

29:02.900 --> 29:06.340
Spitz bit bucked twice, and then jumped away.

29:06.340 --> 29:08.820
He watched Buck carefully.

29:08.820 --> 29:11.620
Buck knew this was the big fight.

29:11.620 --> 29:15.180
Either he or Spitz must die.

29:15.180 --> 29:19.140
Their ears went back, and they growled angrily.

29:19.140 --> 29:24.260
They watched each other carefully, and they circled slowly.

29:24.260 --> 29:29.020
The night was silent, and everything was white in the moonlight.

29:29.020 --> 29:34.260
The other dogs ate the rabbit, and then turned to watch the fight.

29:34.260 --> 29:37.620
Spitz was a great fighter, and he was intelligent.

29:37.620 --> 29:42.420
Buck tried to bite his throat, but Spitz always defended himself.

29:42.420 --> 29:47.300
Every time Buck attacked, Spitz moved away, and bit him on the side.

29:47.300 --> 29:49.820
Soon Buck was covered with blood.

29:49.820 --> 29:51.900
The fight was desperate.

29:51.900 --> 29:54.140
But Buck had a good imagination.

29:54.140 --> 29:58.020
He fought with his instinct, but also with his head.

29:58.020 --> 30:00.380
Buck attacked again.

30:00.380 --> 30:05.100
At the last minute, he went under Spitz and bit his left leg.

30:05.100 --> 30:09.060
The bone broke, and Spitz stood on three legs.

30:09.060 --> 30:13.540
Buck attacked three more times, and then broke his right leg.

30:13.540 --> 30:15.940
There was no hope for Spitz now.

30:15.940 --> 30:19.820
The silent circle of dogs moved closer to Spitz.

30:19.820 --> 30:22.500
They waited for the end.

30:22.500 --> 30:24.460
Then Buck attacked again.

30:24.460 --> 30:27.180
Spitz fell down on the snow.

30:27.180 --> 30:31.060
He disappeared under the circle of the other dogs.

30:31.060 --> 30:33.900
Buck stood and watched.

30:33.900 --> 30:38.620
He was the champion.

30:38.620 --> 30:41.860
Exercise 2, listening.

30:41.860 --> 30:42.860
Hello!

30:42.860 --> 30:46.700
I want to write an article about couriers in the Yukon territory.

30:46.700 --> 30:48.460
What does a courier do?

30:48.460 --> 30:54.780
Well, I take important government papers and documents from Dai'i to Dawson City.

30:54.780 --> 30:57.300
What time do you start traveling in the morning?

30:57.300 --> 31:02.300
I wake up at 6 o'clock, honest to dogs, and start traveling at half past 6.

31:02.300 --> 31:05.340
Well, those are very cold in the Yukon territory.

31:05.340 --> 31:06.660
Oh, yes.

31:06.660 --> 31:10.060
The temperature is about 50 degrees Fahrenheit below zero.

31:10.060 --> 31:12.260
Do you stop to have lunch?

31:12.260 --> 31:14.820
No, we don't have time.

31:14.820 --> 31:17.020
When do you stop to eat and rest?

31:17.020 --> 31:19.740
We stop at 7 o'clock in the evening.

31:19.740 --> 31:21.140
What do you eat?

31:21.140 --> 31:23.020
From Swayanite, eat bread and fish.

31:23.020 --> 31:25.500
The dogs eat only fish.

31:25.500 --> 31:27.300
When did you leave Dai'i?

31:27.300 --> 31:30.380
We left on Thursday, December 6.

31:30.380 --> 31:32.780
When did you arrive in Dawson City?

31:32.780 --> 31:35.900
We arrived on Sunday, December 30.

31:35.900 --> 31:37.420
Do you like your job?

31:37.420 --> 31:41.940
Yes, it's very exciting.

31:41.940 --> 31:46.740
Chapter 6, the new lead dog.

31:46.740 --> 31:52.180
The next morning, Francois could not find spits, and he saw Buck covered with blood.

31:52.180 --> 31:53.740
What did I say?

31:53.740 --> 31:55.380
Buck is a great fighter.

31:55.380 --> 31:56.380
Said Francois.

31:56.380 --> 31:59.580
Perot looked at the wounds on Buck's body and said,

31:59.580 --> 32:02.340
That spits fought like a devil.

32:02.340 --> 32:04.260
And Buck fought like two devils.

32:04.260 --> 32:07.420
Francois said, Now we can travel faster.

32:07.420 --> 32:10.660
No more spits, no more trouble.

32:10.660 --> 32:13.940
Francois started to harness the dogs.

32:13.940 --> 32:16.700
Buck walked to Spitz's old position.

32:16.700 --> 32:20.300
But Francois put Sallak's in the lead position.

32:20.300 --> 32:23.020
Buck jumped angrily at Sallak's.

32:23.020 --> 32:26.220
Eh, Francois cried, Look at that Buck.

32:26.220 --> 32:30.220
He killed Spitz, and now he wants his place.

32:30.220 --> 32:31.540
Go away Buck.

32:31.540 --> 32:34.820
But Buck did not move.

32:34.820 --> 32:36.740
Sallak's was not happy.

32:36.740 --> 32:38.820
He was afraid of Buck.

32:38.820 --> 32:43.940
When Francois turned his back, Buck pushed Sallak's away.

32:43.940 --> 32:46.020
Francois was angry.

32:46.060 --> 32:48.140
Now I'll show you.

32:48.140 --> 32:50.300
He went to get a heavy club.

32:50.300 --> 32:54.180
Buck remembered the man in the red sweater and moved away.

32:54.180 --> 32:55.100
Come here Buck.

32:55.100 --> 32:56.860
Said Francois.

32:56.860 --> 32:58.860
Buck did not obey.

32:58.860 --> 33:03.140
He wanted to be the lead dog because he won the fight with spits.

33:03.140 --> 33:07.820
The two men tried to put on the harness, but he always moved away.

33:07.820 --> 33:08.740
Come here Buck.

33:08.740 --> 33:13.100
Perot said, But Buck did not move.

33:13.100 --> 33:14.580
It was late.

33:14.580 --> 33:18.060
Francois put Sallak's in his old place.

33:18.060 --> 33:21.180
Perot looked at his watch and he was angry.

33:21.180 --> 33:23.260
Put down the club Francois.

33:23.260 --> 33:28.220
Francois put down the club and Buck came to the front of the team.

33:28.220 --> 33:33.580
Francois put on the harness and the sled started moving.

33:33.580 --> 33:36.540
Buck was an excellently dog.

33:36.540 --> 33:38.940
He moved and thought quickly.

33:38.940 --> 33:41.580
The other dogs worked harder with Buck.

33:41.580 --> 33:44.380
The team traveled faster and faster.

33:44.380 --> 33:46.260
Buck is the best dog.

33:46.260 --> 33:47.420
The very best.

33:47.420 --> 33:53.300
Francois said, It was 45 degrees Fahrenheit below zero.

33:53.300 --> 33:57.140
Some days the dogs traveled 60 miles or more.

33:57.140 --> 34:01.300
After 14 days, they reached Skagway.

34:01.300 --> 34:04.260
The dog team was the center of attention.

34:04.260 --> 34:07.980
Then the two men received orders from the Canadian government.

34:07.980 --> 34:11.820
Francois put his arms around Buck and cried.

34:11.820 --> 34:17.100
Then the two men left and Buck did not see them again.

34:17.100 --> 34:20.460
Another man took Buck and his team back to Dawson.

34:20.460 --> 34:25.220
The sled was very heavy because it carried mail for the gold miners.

34:25.220 --> 34:29.420
Buck did not like it, but he and the other dogs worked hard.

34:29.420 --> 34:32.060
It was not an interesting life.

34:32.060 --> 34:34.740
One day was like another.

34:34.740 --> 34:36.980
They started before it was light.

34:36.980 --> 34:41.220
At night they camped and this was the best part of the day.

34:41.220 --> 34:44.820
The dogs ate some fish and rested by the fire.

34:44.820 --> 34:47.940
Buck loved to rest by the fire.

34:47.940 --> 34:52.020
Sometimes he thought of Judge Miller's big house and his life there.

34:52.020 --> 34:57.060
He also thought about the man in the red sweater, the death of Curly and the big fight with

34:57.060 --> 34:58.700
spits.

34:58.700 --> 35:06.780
Other times he remembered his parents, his ancestors and the world of long ago.

35:06.780 --> 35:10.460
The journey was hard and the mail was heavy.

35:10.460 --> 35:12.940
The dogs were tired and weak.

35:12.940 --> 35:15.180
They needed a long rest.

35:15.180 --> 35:18.620
But after only two days they were traveling again.

35:18.620 --> 35:21.340
The dogs and the men were unhappy.

35:21.340 --> 35:24.340
Each night the men took care of their dogs.

35:24.340 --> 35:28.740
They looked at their feet, but the dogs became weaker every day.

35:28.740 --> 35:32.500
Billy cried in his sleep and was very unfriendly.

35:32.500 --> 35:35.140
Dave was tired and ill.

35:35.140 --> 35:37.180
Something was wrong with him.

35:37.180 --> 35:42.260
When they stopped in the evening he laid down and did not stand up until morning.

35:42.260 --> 35:44.580
The men were worried about Dave.

35:44.580 --> 35:47.540
They did not understand his illness.

35:47.540 --> 35:51.500
One day Dave could not pull the sled anymore.

35:51.500 --> 35:54.940
He cried sadly when Sallax took his place.

35:54.940 --> 35:58.300
The next morning Dave could not move.

35:58.300 --> 36:02.380
The driver took his pistol and walked away.

36:02.380 --> 36:06.140
The dogs heard a shot.

36:06.140 --> 36:10.540
The man came back quickly and the sled moved again.

36:10.540 --> 36:14.260
Buck and the other dogs knew what happened to Dave.

36:14.260 --> 36:19.620
Thirty days after leaving Dawson City the team arrived in Skagway.

36:19.620 --> 36:22.300
The dogs were exhausted and thin.

36:22.300 --> 36:24.540
They needed a long rest.

36:24.540 --> 36:28.540
The men needed new strong dogs to pull the sled.

36:28.540 --> 36:31.300
They sold the old tired dogs.

36:31.300 --> 36:36.540
Two American men called Hal and Charles bought Buck and his team.

36:36.540 --> 36:39.100
They bought other dogs too.

36:39.100 --> 36:43.580
Charles was forty years old and Hal was a young man.

36:43.580 --> 36:47.180
Charles's wife Mercedes was also with them.

36:47.180 --> 36:52.860
They knew nothing about life in the Northland and they made many mistakes.

36:52.860 --> 36:57.380
They put too many things on their sled and tried to start.

36:57.380 --> 37:02.900
The dogs pulled hard for a few moments and then stopped.

37:02.900 --> 37:07.060
They could not move because it was too heavy.

37:07.060 --> 37:10.620
These lazy animals cried Hal with a whip in his hand.

37:10.620 --> 37:12.260
They're very weak.

37:12.260 --> 37:13.260
Said a man.

37:13.260 --> 37:14.900
They need a rest.

37:14.900 --> 37:15.900
Nonsense.

37:15.900 --> 37:17.100
They're very lazy.

37:17.100 --> 37:18.100
Said Hal.

37:18.100 --> 37:19.100
Mush.

37:19.100 --> 37:20.100
He cried.

37:20.100 --> 37:21.660
Mush.

37:21.660 --> 37:25.140
Hal whipped the dogs again and again.

37:25.140 --> 37:26.140
Another man said.

37:26.140 --> 37:29.900
I don't care about you but I care about the dogs.

37:29.900 --> 37:33.820
Break the ice around the sled and then the dogs can pull.

37:33.820 --> 37:38.020
Hal broke the ice and the sled moved forward.

37:38.020 --> 37:41.380
The unhappy team moved on.

37:41.380 --> 37:45.220
Day after day Hal whipped the poor dogs.

37:45.220 --> 37:47.660
He gave them little food to eat.

37:47.660 --> 37:50.580
They were very tired and very hungry.

37:50.580 --> 37:53.020
They looked like skeletons.

37:53.020 --> 37:55.460
They hurt himself and was shot.

37:55.460 --> 37:57.860
Billy and some other dogs died.

37:57.860 --> 38:01.380
Soon we will all die.

38:01.380 --> 38:04.860
Buck thought.

38:04.860 --> 38:09.460
Chapter 7 For the Love of a Man

38:09.460 --> 38:12.900
Only five dogs reached John Thornton's camp.

38:12.900 --> 38:16.740
Joe, Pike, Sallak's, Teak and Buck.

38:16.740 --> 38:20.380
They fell on the ground and could not move.

38:20.380 --> 38:22.740
They were almost dead.

38:22.740 --> 38:27.420
It was nearly the end of winter and it was a beautiful day.

38:27.420 --> 38:29.540
John Thornton was repairing an axe.

38:29.540 --> 38:32.060
Is it safe to cross the river here?

38:32.060 --> 38:33.060
Asked Hal.

38:33.060 --> 38:35.180
Oh no, it's very dangerous.

38:35.180 --> 38:36.700
The ice is too thin.

38:36.700 --> 38:38.820
And Sir Thornton.

38:38.820 --> 38:41.900
Hal looked at him and said, I don't believe you.

38:41.900 --> 38:43.580
We must go to Dawson.

38:43.580 --> 38:45.460
He took his whip and cried.

38:45.460 --> 38:48.420
Come on Buck, let's go.

38:48.420 --> 38:52.700
Thornton knew these people were stupid and did not understand.

38:52.700 --> 38:55.220
The team did not move.

38:55.220 --> 38:58.460
After a while Sallak slowly stood up.

38:58.460 --> 39:01.140
Joe was crying but he stood up.

39:01.140 --> 39:04.340
Pike tried twice and fell down.

39:04.340 --> 39:06.660
The third time he stood up.

39:06.660 --> 39:08.380
Buck did not try.

39:08.380 --> 39:12.340
Hal whipped him but Buck did not move.

39:12.340 --> 39:14.900
Thornton wanted to speak but he did not.

39:14.900 --> 39:17.380
Hal was furious and took the club.

39:17.380 --> 39:20.980
He hit Buck again and again.

39:20.980 --> 39:23.780
But Buck did not want to stand up.

39:23.780 --> 39:26.900
He had a strange feeling of doom.

39:26.900 --> 39:29.820
He saw thin ice in front of him.

39:29.820 --> 39:35.100
After so much suffering, he did not feel the club.

39:35.100 --> 39:38.820
Then suddenly Thornton jumped on Hal and threw him to the ground.

39:38.820 --> 39:41.900
Don't hit that dog again or I'll kill you.

39:41.900 --> 39:42.900
Thornton cried.

39:42.900 --> 39:44.380
It's my dog.

39:44.380 --> 39:45.380
Said Hal.

39:45.380 --> 39:47.060
Go away or I'll hit you too.

39:47.060 --> 39:49.140
I'm going to Dawson.

39:49.140 --> 39:51.860
Thornton stood between him and Buck.

39:51.860 --> 39:54.780
Hal took out his long knife.

39:54.780 --> 39:57.180
Thornton knocked it out of Hal's hand.

39:57.180 --> 40:01.380
Then Thornton picked it up and cut Buck's harness.

40:01.380 --> 40:03.340
Hal did not want to fight.

40:03.340 --> 40:04.700
Buck was almost dead.

40:04.700 --> 40:08.860
A few minutes later Hal and the sled went along the river.

40:08.860 --> 40:14.940
Buck raised his head and saw Pike, Sallak's Joe and Teak pulling the sled.

40:14.940 --> 40:17.020
Thornton examined Buck's body.

40:17.020 --> 40:19.700
He was looking for broken bones.

40:19.700 --> 40:22.180
Buck was terribly thin and weak.

40:22.180 --> 40:27.020
You have many wounds, but no broken bones.

40:27.020 --> 40:28.900
Said Thornton.

40:28.900 --> 40:32.300
Both dog and man watched the sled.

40:32.300 --> 40:35.660
It was crossing the ice in the middle of the river.

40:35.660 --> 40:40.060
Suddenly the back of the sled went down and the front went up.

40:40.060 --> 40:41.740
There was a lot of screaming.

40:42.180 --> 40:48.340
Then a big piece of ice broke and the dogs and the people disappeared.

40:48.340 --> 40:51.500
John Thornton and Buck looked at each other.

40:51.500 --> 40:53.180
You poor dog.

40:53.180 --> 40:57.100
Said Thornton and Buck licked his hand.

40:57.100 --> 41:00.100
John Thornton was ill all winter.

41:00.100 --> 41:03.980
His friends left him at White River while they went to Dawson.

41:03.980 --> 41:07.940
Thornton had a lot of food and he was comfortable.

41:07.940 --> 41:11.300
Now it was spring and he was better.

41:11.300 --> 41:15.900
During the warm spring days he and Buck sat by the river.

41:15.900 --> 41:20.060
Buck watched the water and listened to the birds.

41:20.060 --> 41:22.380
He needed the long rest.

41:22.380 --> 41:26.500
Slowly he became stronger and fatter.

41:26.500 --> 41:29.820
John Thornton had two other dogs.

41:29.820 --> 41:34.140
Skeet was a small dog and she made friends with Buck.

41:34.140 --> 41:36.980
When Buck was ill she took care of him.

41:36.980 --> 41:39.700
She washed his cuts with her tongue.

41:39.700 --> 41:42.380
Nigg was a big friendly dog.

41:42.380 --> 41:45.380
His eyes laughed when Buck became stronger.

41:45.380 --> 41:47.540
The three dogs played together.

41:47.540 --> 41:50.580
Thornton sometimes played with him.

41:50.580 --> 41:52.900
The days passed happily.

41:52.900 --> 41:56.620
For the first time Buck learned to love.

41:56.620 --> 42:01.660
He and Judge Miller were very good friends but Buck did not love him.

42:01.660 --> 42:07.100
John Thornton saved Buck's life and he was the perfect master.

42:07.180 --> 42:10.660
He loved his dogs and took good care of them.

42:10.660 --> 42:13.060
The dogs were like his children.

42:13.060 --> 42:14.980
He always talked to Buck.

42:14.980 --> 42:19.220
He took Buck's head between his hands and shook it lovingly.

42:19.220 --> 42:21.140
He adored Thornton.

42:21.140 --> 42:26.220
When Thornton touched him or spoke to him he was wild with happiness.

42:26.220 --> 42:30.060
He sat near Thornton and looked at his face for hours.

42:30.060 --> 42:33.220
At first Buck followed Thornton everywhere.

42:33.220 --> 42:37.420
He did not want Thornton to leave like Francois and Perot.

42:37.420 --> 42:42.420
Buck was very happy with Thornton but he was a dog of the Northland.

42:42.420 --> 42:46.900
He dreamed of other animals and heard them calling him.

42:46.900 --> 42:50.500
It was the call of the wild.

42:50.500 --> 42:53.580
Sometimes Buck wanted to answer the call.

42:53.580 --> 42:59.220
He often went into the forest but he always returned to Thornton.

42:59.220 --> 43:01.660
Buck was not interested in other men.

43:01.660 --> 43:07.220
When Thornton's friends Hans and Pete returned Buck did not notice them.

43:07.220 --> 43:11.820
He knew they were Thornton's good friends and so he accepted them.

43:11.820 --> 43:16.300
Hans and Pete saw that Buck loved only Thornton and no one else.

43:16.300 --> 43:19.740
He was always happy to obey Thornton.

43:19.740 --> 43:23.140
One day they were in Circle City.

43:23.140 --> 43:26.900
Black Burton was a bad and cruel man.

43:26.900 --> 43:30.740
He was in a saloon and he was fighting with another man.

43:30.740 --> 43:32.740
Thornton tried to stop them.

43:32.740 --> 43:35.220
Buck sat in a corner and watched.

43:35.220 --> 43:37.860
Burton hit Thornton and he almost fell.

43:37.860 --> 43:43.020
It was a loud growl and Buck jumped into the air at Burton's throat.

43:43.020 --> 43:45.860
The man put up his arm and saved his life.

43:45.860 --> 43:49.060
Then he fell to the ground with Buck on top of him.

43:49.060 --> 43:51.220
Buck bit into his throat.

43:51.220 --> 43:53.500
Some people pulled Buck off the man.

43:53.500 --> 43:56.540
A doctor arrived and examined Burton's throat.

43:56.540 --> 43:59.620
The dog attacked only because Thornton was in danger.

44:00.620 --> 44:06.620
From that day Buck's name became famous all over the Northland.

44:06.620 --> 44:11.620
In the fall of that year Buck saved Thornton's life another time.

44:11.620 --> 44:13.620
The three men were going down the river.

44:13.620 --> 44:17.620
Thornton was in the boat and Hans and Pete were on the river bank.

44:17.620 --> 44:20.620
They were holding the boat with a rope.

44:20.620 --> 44:23.620
Buck was on the bank and watched his master.

44:23.620 --> 44:26.620
Soon they came to a dangerous part of the river.

44:26.620 --> 44:30.620
The boat was going too fast because the current was strong.

44:30.620 --> 44:34.620
Hans pulled the rope to stop the boat but it turned over.

44:34.620 --> 44:36.620
Thornton fell into the water.

44:36.620 --> 44:40.620
Buck jumped in immediately and swam to his master.

44:40.620 --> 44:45.620
Thornton took Buck's tail and Buck swam bravely towards the river bank.

44:45.620 --> 44:49.620
But they moved slowly because the river pushed them to the rocks.

44:49.620 --> 44:53.620
We can't get to the river bank because the current is too strong.

44:53.620 --> 44:56.620
He held on to a rock and let go of Buck's tail.

44:56.620 --> 44:59.620
Then he cried, go Buck, go!

44:59.620 --> 45:02.620
Buck obeyed and swam to the river bank.

45:02.620 --> 45:05.620
Hans and Pete pulled him out of the river.

45:05.620 --> 45:08.620
We must work fast to save Thornton. He's in great danger.

45:08.620 --> 45:09.620
Said Pete.

45:09.620 --> 45:13.620
They tied a rope around Buck and he jumped into the river again.

45:13.620 --> 45:17.620
The river carried him past Thornton but he finally reached him.

45:17.620 --> 45:22.620
Thornton held on to Buck and Hans and Pete pulled the rope very hard.

45:22.620 --> 45:26.620
Thornton and Buck disappeared under the water.

45:26.620 --> 45:30.620
When Hans and Pete pulled them out, they both seemed dead.

45:30.620 --> 45:33.620
But they slowly opened their eyes.

45:33.620 --> 45:38.620
Thornton examined Buck's body and found three broken bones.

45:38.620 --> 45:41.620
We must camp here until Buck is better.

45:41.620 --> 45:44.620
Said Thornton.

45:44.620 --> 45:48.620
Chapter 8. The winner.

45:48.620 --> 45:54.620
At Dawson that winter, Buck did something that made him very famous in the Northland.

45:54.620 --> 45:59.620
Thornton, Hans and Pete wanted to go to the east to look for gold.

45:59.620 --> 46:01.620
But they needed money.

46:01.620 --> 46:04.620
One day, they were at the El Dorado saloon.

46:04.620 --> 46:08.620
My dog can pull a sled with 500 pounds on it.

46:08.620 --> 46:09.620
Said one man.

46:09.620 --> 46:13.620
Well, my dog can pull 600 pounds.

46:13.620 --> 46:14.620
Said another man.

46:14.620 --> 46:17.620
Really? Well, my dog can pull 700 pounds.

46:17.620 --> 46:20.620
Said a third man called Mathewson.

46:20.620 --> 46:21.620
That's nothing.

46:21.620 --> 46:23.620
Said Thornton.

46:23.620 --> 46:25.620
Buck can pull a thousand pounds.

46:25.620 --> 46:29.620
Can he move the sled when it's frozen to the ice and then pull it 100 yards?

46:29.620 --> 46:30.620
Asked Mathewson.

46:30.620 --> 46:32.620
Yes, he can.

46:32.620 --> 46:33.620
Said Thornton.

46:33.620 --> 46:34.620
Well?

46:34.620 --> 46:35.620
Said Mathewson.

46:35.620 --> 46:39.620
I've got a thousand dollars here and I say he can't.

46:39.620 --> 46:43.620
He took a bag of gold and put it on the table.

46:43.620 --> 46:45.620
Nobody spoke.

46:45.620 --> 46:49.620
Thornton thought, I know Buck is strong.

46:49.620 --> 46:52.620
But is he really so strong?

46:52.620 --> 46:56.620
The men at the saloon looked at him silently and waited.

46:56.620 --> 46:59.620
Thornton did not have a thousand dollars.

46:59.620 --> 47:01.620
And his friends did not either.

47:01.620 --> 47:04.620
I've got a sled outside with a thousand pounds on it.

47:04.620 --> 47:07.620
Mathewson said, do you want to try?

47:07.620 --> 47:10.620
Thornton did not know what to say.

47:10.620 --> 47:12.620
He looked at all the men.

47:12.620 --> 47:15.620
Then he saw his old friend, Jim O'Brien.

47:15.620 --> 47:18.620
Can you lend me a thousand dollars Jim?

47:18.620 --> 47:20.620
Thornton said softly.

47:20.620 --> 47:22.620
Sure, said O'Brien.

47:22.620 --> 47:24.620
But I don't think your dog can do it.

47:24.620 --> 47:27.620
Everyone went into the street.

47:27.620 --> 47:30.620
A lot of men stood around Mathewson's sled.

47:30.620 --> 47:35.620
The sled was frozen to the ice because it was terribly cold.

47:35.620 --> 47:39.620
Mathewson was sure Buck could not win and said,

47:39.620 --> 47:41.620
I'm paying another four hundred dollars.

47:41.620 --> 47:43.620
What about you?

47:43.620 --> 47:47.620
Thornton, Hans, and Pete talked together.

47:47.620 --> 47:52.620
They had only two hundred dollars and they added them to the thousand dollars.

47:52.620 --> 47:55.620
Buck felt the excitement in the air.

47:55.620 --> 47:59.620
He knew he must do something great for Thornton.

47:59.620 --> 48:02.620
Buck was in perfect condition.

48:02.620 --> 48:04.620
He was a splendid dog.

48:04.620 --> 48:08.620
Thornton sat down on the snow next to Buck.

48:08.620 --> 48:13.620
He held Buck's head in his hands and spoke softly in his ear.

48:13.620 --> 48:17.620
If you love me Buck, if you love me.

48:17.620 --> 48:19.620
Buck understood.

48:19.620 --> 48:23.620
He took Thornton's hand between his teeth and then let go.

48:23.620 --> 48:27.620
He often did this as a sign of his love.

48:27.620 --> 48:29.620
Everyone was silent.

48:29.620 --> 48:32.620
Thornton stood up and said, ready Buck?

48:32.620 --> 48:34.620
Buck pulled on the harness.

48:34.620 --> 48:35.620
Right!

48:36.620 --> 48:39.620
Buck pulled to the right and stopped suddenly.

48:39.620 --> 48:40.620
Now left!

48:40.620 --> 48:41.620
Cried Thornton.

48:41.620 --> 48:43.620
Buck pulled to the left.

48:43.620 --> 48:45.620
The ice was breaking.

48:45.620 --> 48:47.620
Now, mush!

48:47.620 --> 48:49.620
Buck started to pull.

48:49.620 --> 48:52.620
His strong body pulled harder and harder.

48:52.620 --> 48:54.620
The sled moved a little.

48:54.620 --> 48:58.620
Suddenly it started to go forward on the snow.

48:58.620 --> 49:01.620
Buck pulled it for one hundred yards.

49:01.620 --> 49:03.620
He was the winner.

49:03.620 --> 49:06.620
The men shouted and threw their hats in the air.

49:06.620 --> 49:09.620
Thornton was on the snow with Buck.

49:09.620 --> 49:11.620
He took his head and shook it.

49:11.620 --> 49:13.620
He was crying with happiness.

49:13.620 --> 49:16.620
Buck had Thornton's hand between his teeth.

49:16.620 --> 49:23.620
In five minutes, Buck made one thousand six hundred dollars for Thornton and his friends.

49:23.620 --> 49:28.620
With this money, they could travel to the east to look for a lost gold mine.

49:28.620 --> 49:30.620
No one knew where it was.

49:30.620 --> 49:32.620
It was a mystery.

49:32.620 --> 49:37.620
The three men with Buck and six other dogs started to go east.

49:37.620 --> 49:42.620
They traveled up the Stewart River and into the Mackenzie Mountains.

49:42.620 --> 49:45.620
Thornton was not afraid of the wild.

49:45.620 --> 49:47.620
He hunted his food during the day.

49:47.620 --> 49:49.620
Buck was very happy.

49:49.620 --> 49:52.620
He loved hunting, fishing and traveling.

49:52.620 --> 49:55.620
They camped in different places and looked for gold.

49:55.620 --> 50:01.620
In the summer they built small boats and crossed mountain lakes and went down rivers.

50:01.620 --> 50:06.620
The months passed and they continued to travel in the unknown country.

50:06.620 --> 50:12.620
In the winter they found an old cabin, but they did not find the gold mine.

50:12.620 --> 50:17.620
Then in the spring they found a stream with gold in it.

50:17.620 --> 50:19.620
It looked like yellow butter.

50:19.620 --> 50:23.620
Every day the men worked hard and found lots of gold.

50:23.620 --> 50:26.620
They put it in many big bags.

50:26.620 --> 50:30.620
Each bag had fifty pounds of gold.

50:30.620 --> 50:34.620
The dogs did nothing except watch the men and eat.

50:34.620 --> 50:38.620
Buck spent many hours sitting by the fire and dreaming.

50:38.620 --> 50:42.620
Sometimes during the day he heard a call from the forest.

50:42.620 --> 50:46.620
He listened and ran off into the forest.

50:46.620 --> 50:50.620
He loved running under the tall trees and looking at the birds.

50:50.620 --> 50:52.620
One night he woke up suddenly.

50:52.620 --> 50:54.620
He heard the call again.

50:54.620 --> 50:58.620
It came from the forest and it was a long howl.

50:58.620 --> 51:02.620
He ran into the forest and followed the sound.

51:02.620 --> 51:07.620
He came to an open space in the trees and saw a wolf.

51:07.620 --> 51:11.620
He was sitting and his nose was up in the air.

51:11.620 --> 51:13.620
He was looking at the sky.

51:13.620 --> 51:17.620
Buck walked towards him slowly and silently.

51:17.620 --> 51:21.620
The wolf stopped howling and ran away.

51:21.620 --> 51:23.620
Buck followed him.

51:23.620 --> 51:26.620
After some time the wolf stopped and growled at Buck.

51:26.620 --> 51:30.620
He was afraid because Buck was much bigger.

51:30.620 --> 51:32.620
But Buck did not want to fight.

51:32.620 --> 51:35.620
He wanted to make friends with the wolf.

51:35.620 --> 51:39.620
The wolf understood and they touched noses.

51:39.620 --> 51:42.620
They became friends and played together.

51:42.620 --> 51:46.620
They ran for hours through the forest and under the open sky.

51:46.620 --> 51:48.620
Old memories came back to Buck.

51:48.620 --> 51:50.620
He was very happy.

51:50.620 --> 51:55.620
They stopped by a stream to drink and Buck remembered John Thornton.

51:55.620 --> 51:57.620
The wolf wanted Buck to follow him.

51:57.620 --> 52:00.620
But Buck turned and slowly went back.

52:00.620 --> 52:02.620
The wolf followed him for a while.

52:02.620 --> 52:05.620
Then he sat down and howled.

52:05.620 --> 52:10.620
It was a sad howl.

52:10.620 --> 52:13.620
Thornton was eating dinner when Buck returned.

52:13.620 --> 52:16.620
He jumped all over Thornton and licked his face.

52:16.620 --> 52:20.620
For two days and nights Buck never left camp.

52:20.620 --> 52:24.620
He followed Thornton everywhere but soon Buck heard the call again.

52:24.620 --> 52:28.620
He thought about his wild brother in the forest.

52:28.620 --> 52:30.620
Buck began to sleep out at night.

52:30.620 --> 52:33.620
He stayed away from camp for three or four days.

52:33.620 --> 52:36.620
Once he stayed away for a week.

52:36.620 --> 52:40.620
He looked for his wild brother but could not find him.

52:40.620 --> 52:44.620
He fished in the streams and killed animals for food.

52:44.620 --> 52:48.620
Every part of his body was alive and healthy.

52:48.620 --> 52:51.620
He was stronger and faster than other dogs.

52:52.620 --> 52:55.620
There was so much energy in Buck.

52:55.620 --> 52:59.620
One day Buck was going to the forest and Thornton said

52:59.620 --> 53:01.620
What a fantastic dog.

53:01.620 --> 53:04.620
Hans and Pete agreed.

53:07.620 --> 53:10.620
Chapter 9 The Call of the Wild

53:10.620 --> 53:14.620
In the fall many moose came to the valley because it was warmer.

53:14.620 --> 53:17.620
Buck wanted to hunt a big moose.

53:17.620 --> 53:21.620
The biggest moose was six feet tall and had enormous antlers.

53:21.620 --> 53:24.620
He was much bigger and stronger than Buck.

53:24.620 --> 53:28.620
When he saw Buck he growled angrily.

53:28.620 --> 53:30.620
Buck followed the moose for many hours.

53:30.620 --> 53:32.620
He was clever and thought.

53:32.620 --> 53:36.620
I must separate him from his group.

53:36.620 --> 53:41.620
It was not easy but by evening the moose was away from his group.

53:41.620 --> 53:43.620
Buck started to attack him.

53:43.620 --> 53:46.620
Wild animals are patient.

53:46.620 --> 53:48.620
They do not hurry.

53:48.620 --> 53:52.620
They wait for the right moment and then they attack.

53:52.620 --> 53:54.620
Buck knew how to wait.

53:54.620 --> 53:58.620
For four days Buck attacked and jumped away.

53:58.620 --> 54:01.620
Then he danced in front of the big moose.

54:01.620 --> 54:03.620
He never left him alone.

54:03.620 --> 54:07.620
The moose could not eat, drink, sleep or rest.

54:07.620 --> 54:12.620
He became very tired and very weak and stopped for long periods.

54:12.620 --> 54:15.620
So Buck ate, drank and rested.

54:15.620 --> 54:20.620
At the end of the fourth day Buck killed the big moose.

54:20.620 --> 54:27.620
For a day and a night he stayed by the dead moose and ate and slept.

54:27.620 --> 54:33.620
When he was rested and strong he decided to return to John Thornton.

54:33.620 --> 54:39.620
When Buck was five miles from camp he smelled something strange, something terrible.

54:39.620 --> 54:41.620
He started running fast.

54:41.620 --> 54:43.620
The forest was silent.

54:43.620 --> 54:46.620
There were no birds and no small animals.

54:46.620 --> 54:50.620
Near some trees he found the dead body of Nigg.

54:50.620 --> 54:53.620
He had an arrow in his body.

54:53.620 --> 54:56.620
He found another sled dog with an arrow in his neck.

54:56.620 --> 55:00.620
Near the camp Buck heard voices singing.

55:00.620 --> 55:05.620
Then he found Hans body with arrows in his back.

55:05.620 --> 55:09.620
A wild, terrible anger grew in Buck.

55:09.620 --> 55:12.620
He could not control his anger.

55:12.620 --> 55:18.620
He saw the Yehat Indians dancing at Thornton's camp and he suddenly attacked them.

55:18.620 --> 55:20.620
He wanted to destroy them.

55:20.620 --> 55:22.620
Buck was faster than the wind.

55:22.620 --> 55:26.620
He jumped at the Indians with all his strength and anger.

55:26.620 --> 55:29.620
He cut the throat of two Indians with his sharp teeth.

55:29.620 --> 55:33.620
Nothing could stop him and he killed many Yehats.

55:33.620 --> 55:35.620
He was like a devil.

55:35.620 --> 55:39.620
The Indians escaped into the forest but Buck followed them.

55:39.620 --> 55:43.620
When Buck returned to the camp he found Pete's body.

55:43.620 --> 55:46.620
He followed Thornton's smell to a pool.

55:46.620 --> 55:50.620
Buck knew Thornton's body was in the pool.

55:50.620 --> 55:53.620
He stayed by the pool all day.

55:53.620 --> 55:56.620
He knew John Thornton was dead.

55:56.620 --> 56:00.620
Now he was very sad and alone.

56:00.620 --> 56:05.620
When he looked at the dead Yehats he was proud of himself.

56:05.620 --> 56:08.620
That night there was a full moon.

56:08.620 --> 56:11.620
Buck heard the sounds of the forest.

56:11.620 --> 56:13.620
They became louder.

56:13.620 --> 56:18.620
It was the call of the wild and he was ready to obey.

56:18.620 --> 56:21.620
John Thornton was dead.

56:21.620 --> 56:24.620
He was completely free.

56:24.620 --> 56:27.620
A wolf pack entered Buck's valley.

56:27.620 --> 56:29.620
He watched them silently.

56:29.620 --> 56:33.620
They were afraid because Buck was so big.

56:33.620 --> 56:38.620
Then one wolf jumped at Buck and he attacked and broke the wolf's neck.

56:38.620 --> 56:41.620
Three other wolves jumped at him but he attacked them.

56:41.620 --> 56:45.620
Finally all the wolf pack attacked Buck.

56:45.620 --> 56:48.620
He jumped at them with his great strength and intelligence.

56:48.620 --> 56:50.620
They could not stop him.

56:50.620 --> 56:53.620
After half an hour the pack went away.

56:53.620 --> 56:55.620
They were very tired.

56:55.620 --> 56:58.620
One wolf was friendly and went close to Buck.

56:58.620 --> 57:00.620
Buck remembered him.

57:00.620 --> 57:03.620
It was his wild brother.

57:03.620 --> 57:05.620
They touched noses.

57:05.620 --> 57:08.620
Other wolves came to make friends.

57:08.620 --> 57:13.620
An old wolf sat down, looked at the moon and howled.

57:13.620 --> 57:16.620
The other sat down and howled too.

57:16.620 --> 57:19.620
Buck did the same.

57:19.620 --> 57:23.620
Soon the wolves were all around Buck and smelled him.

57:23.620 --> 57:27.620
Then they ran into the forest and Buck ran with them.

57:27.620 --> 57:30.620
His wild brother ran by his side.

57:30.620 --> 57:34.620
Perhaps this is the end of Buck's story.

57:34.620 --> 57:42.620
But after a few years the Yehat Indians saw that some wolves had brown in their grey coats.

57:42.620 --> 57:47.620
They also saw a ghost dog at the front of the wolf pack.

57:47.620 --> 57:52.620
When the Yehats follow the moose they do not enter a certain valley.

57:52.620 --> 57:56.620
In the summer there is a visitor in that valley.

57:56.620 --> 58:00.620
A big golden brown wolf.

58:00.620 --> 58:03.620
He is bigger than any other wolf.

58:03.620 --> 58:10.620
He goes to a yellow stream, stops there and then howls.

58:10.620 --> 58:13.620
But he is not always alone.

58:13.620 --> 58:16.620
He is the leader of the wolf pack.

58:16.620 --> 58:22.620
He runs in the moonlight and sings the song of the pack.

58:22.620 --> 58:25.620
Exercise two, listening.

58:25.620 --> 58:28.620
Why are you afraid of the valley?

58:28.620 --> 58:32.620
We are afraid of that valley because a ghost dog lives there.

58:32.620 --> 58:34.620
A ghost dog?

58:34.620 --> 58:39.620
Yes, a big brown dog with long white fangs.

58:39.620 --> 58:41.620
He is bigger than a wolf.

58:41.620 --> 58:43.620
He growls at people.

58:43.620 --> 58:48.620
In the summer he sits near a yellow stream and looks at the water.

58:48.620 --> 58:50.620
Sometimes he cries.

58:50.620 --> 58:54.620
At night he looks at the stars and howls.

58:54.620 --> 58:56.620
Is he always alone?

58:56.620 --> 58:59.620
No, he is the leader of a wolf pack.

58:59.620 --> 59:03.620
He runs in the valley and the wolves follow him.

59:03.620 --> 59:06.620
Is there any gold in the yellow stream?

59:06.620 --> 59:08.620
Yes, there is lots of gold.

59:08.620 --> 59:11.620
But everyone is afraid to enter the valley.

59:11.620 --> 59:13.620
Do you hunt the moose in the valley?

59:13.620 --> 59:15.620
No, never.

59:15.620 --> 59:19.620
A ghost dog is very dangerous.

